ch the structures of the university and the people working within it continue to keep their traditionally marginalized members relegated to symbolic status, somewhere outside the center. Reyes confronts the impossibility of success in the midst of competing and contradictory needs—from navigating coded language, to balancing professional expectations with care-taking responsibilities, to combating the literal exclusions of outmoded and hierarchical rules. Her searing commentary takes on, with sensitivity and fury, the urgent call for academic justice.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aCollege teachersxTenurezUnited States. 0aDiscrimination in higher educationzUnited States. 0aMinority college teacherszUnited StatesxSocial conditions. 0aMinority women college teacherszUnited StatesvBiography. 0aRacism in higher educationzUnited States. 0aSexism in higher educationzUnited States. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Discrimination & Race Relations.2bisacsh  aacademia.  aadvice.  afaculty.  afeminism.  agender.  agraduate school.  agraduate students.  amemoir.  amotherhood.  arace/ethnicity.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertStanford University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311076648640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150363368140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503633681423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781503633681/original  a978-3-11-076648-6  Stanford University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  aGBV-deGruyter-alles